body:
Worked out I could actually use a more recent ONNX Runtime commit (I had assumed the one mentioned https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2684#issuecomment-568548387 was the most recent commit with the correct CUDA/cuDNN/TensorRT versions). After building ONNX Runtime 1.1.0 (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/commit/273868eaa55431164a2e5b5a94b8941bd550a7c3) I no longer see any `Found unsupport node: XXX` messages, but otherwise the error is the same:
```
2020-03-18 20:08:48.705396756 [W:onnxruntime:Default, tensorrt_execution_provider.h:28 log] [2020-03-18 20:08:48 WARNING] Calling isShapeTensor before the entire network is constructed may result in an inaccurate result.
2020-03-18 20:08:48.900676539 [W:onnxruntime:Default, tensorrt_execution_provider.h:28 log] [2020-03-18 20:08:48 WARNING] Setting layouts of network and plugin input/output tensors to linear, as 3D operators are found and 3D non-linear IO formats are not supported, yet.
2020-03-18 20:08:50.657570787 [W:onnxruntime:Default, tensorrt_execution_provider.h:28 log] [2020-03-18 20:08:50   ERROR] ../rtSafe/safeRuntime.cpp (25) - Cuda Error in allocate: 2 (out of memory)
2020-03-18 20:08:50.667367447 [W:onnxruntime:Default, tensorrt_execution_provider.h:28 log] [2020-03-18 20:08:50   ERROR] ../rtSafe/safeRuntime.cpp (25) - Cuda Error in allocate: 2 (out of memory)
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "test_onnx.py", line 87, in <module>
    main()
  File "test_onnx.py", line 61, in main
    ort_session = ort.InferenceSession(args.model, providers=['TensorrtExecutionProvider','CUDAExecutionProvider','CPUExecutionProvider'])
  File "/home/callum/.local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/session.py", line 25, in __init__
    self._load_model(providers)
  File "/home/callum/.local/lib/python3.6/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/session.py", line 43, in _load_model
    self._sess.load_model(providers)
onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state.EPFail: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 11 : EP_FAIL : TensorRT EP could not build Engine for fused node: TensorrtExecutionProvider_TRTKernel_0_0
```

Above I mentioned that I get `Cuda Error in free` when ORT_TENSORRT_MAX_WORKSPACE is too small but it also seems to happen when it is too big.

Neither of the tegrastats outputs suggest particularly high memory usage although I guess its quite possible that it is missing the peaks.

I have been playing with the ORT_TENSORRT_MAX_PARTITION_ITERATIONS value. My understanding is that every time TensorRT doesn't support an operation the graph will be partitioned, so that the unsupported node(s) is run using a fallback provider (CUDA or CPU). If we have to partitions more than ORT_TENSORRT_MAX_PARTITION_ITERATIONS then the whole graph falls back to the fallback provider.

- With a value of 1 I get no warnings and the graph falls back to another provider and runs successfully.
- With a value of 2 I get the following warning and the graph falls back to another provider and runs successfully:
```
2020-03-19 09:03:50.109044117 [W:onnxruntime:Default, tensorrt_execution_provider.h:28 log] [2020-03-19 09:03:50 WARNING] Calling isShapeTensor before the entire network is constructed may result in an inaccurate result.
```
